text: i've always had an entrepreneurial and
curious mindset during my studies in
computing i also ran my own company to
develop mobile apps and e-commerce
websites for fitness professionals along
with my own fitness blog using wordpress
this gave me so many insights into how
customers use technology and so many
learnings from wins and losses of my own
that prepared me for life at aws
in 2016 i joined aws as a graduate cloud
support associate in this team i learned
the fundamentals of how the cloud works
before transitioning into the serverless
support team
today i'm a senior solutions architect
here in dublin ireland in my role i
maintain deep relationships with
developers engineers and technical
leadership like chief technology
officers within my customers
in ireland i work with every shape and
size of customer from startup all the
way up to enterprise i take their
business challenges and translate them
into technical solutions on aws whether
that's migrating existing apps building
new apps saving costs on infrastructure
enabling staff or just being their
trusted architectural advisor
technology aside the most important
skill you need as a solutions architect
is communication
you need to take deeply technical topics
and translate them into business
language and vice versa
perhaps the most rewarding thing about
my role is the impact that aws has on
society
in the past 18 months i've been directly
involved in a number of projects related
to the covet 19 pandemic such as helping
pharmaceutical companies to develop new
apps to improve human health enabling
gps to quickly spin up amazon connect
call centers to deal with backlogs
supporting charities and developing
fully serverless donation platforms and
helping airlines innovate to assist in a
strong return to service just to name a
few at aws i'm surrounded by ex-cto's
founders book authors and lots of
intelligent people working with and
learning from my colleagues is very
exciting and provides plenty of
opportunity to learn and grow our ceo
andy jassy once said there's no
compression algorithm for experience but
this is definitely the closest thing
that i've found
